Support for brake manoeuvre in critical situations is now required
As with the ABS anti-blocking brake system and as with the ESP stability control at the moment, the aid systems for braking in emergency must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly approved passenger cars and small carriers, for the rest of the vehicles a carence period was established by the end of February 2011.
The measures adopted by the European Union aim to improve the protection of footgängers, but these brake systems can also help to prevent many accidents because of their working manner.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exercise more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical brake manufacturing which the system recognizes using the brake strength carried out by the driver on the brake spedal.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an inquiry by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident before the collaboration no longer came to step to the brake spedal and half of them had not broken with full strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the other hand, the brake aid takes into the brake system with maximum power and thus reduces the brake time and thus also the brake distance that a car leaves at the brake process.
According to a EU study, up to 1.100 fatal accidents that affect footing users could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with such an emergency brake assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - it is expected that every fourth accident could be prevented with personal damage - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency brake systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time it already exerts a light pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him to increase pressure on the brake spedal if necessary.
